07. Hatching success

Elliott Schmidt

2024-05-09

Scenario

Within this chapter developmental plasticity was explored within Acanthochromis polyacanthus that were collected from two different regions (i.e., low-latitude, Cairns, and high-latitude, Mackay). Fish were held in common garden experiments at 28.5 C. Reproductive meterics are only relevant to parental fish. Understanding potential differences in reproduction within fish from low- and high-latitude populations will provide basis of where juveniles are starting from.

Set working directory

knitr::opts_knit$set(root.dir=working.dir)

Import data

Note that when making the datasheet, each clutch was designated an experimental_number that is associated with which experiment(s) clutches were involved in, therefore when importing the data, we will filter data to give us only clutches that were used in the relevent developmental plasticity experiment. We are also dropping one clutch that was found only when individuals hatched, meaning we dont know the clutch size, or hatching success

clutch_data <- read_delim("import_files/clutch_data_2022_2023.txt", 
    delim = "\t", escape_double = FALSE, 
    trim_ws = TRUE) |> 
  mutate(PROJECT_CODE = factor(PROJECT_CODE)) |>
  filter(PROJECT_CODE == "2"| 
         PROJECT_CODE == "3"|
         PROJECT_CODE == "6"|
         PROJECT_CODE == "7") |> 
  drop_na(EGG_COUNT)

We are left with 20 clutches; 12 from the Core region (from 11 unique pairs), and 8 from the leading region (from 5 unique pairs).

Data manipulation

clutch_data2 <- clutch_data |> 
  mutate(CLUTCH_NUMBER = as.factor(CLUTCH_NUMBER), 
         MALE = factor(MALE), 
         FEMALE = factor(FEMALE), 
         REGION = factor(REGION), 
         POPULATION = factor(POPULATION),
         CLUTCH_ORDER = factor(CLUTCH_ORDER),
         DATE_OF_HATCH = as.Date(DATE_OF_HATCH, format = "%d/%m/%Y"), 
         FEMALE_MASS = coalesce(FEMALE_MASS, MALE_MASS))

Exploratory data analysis

Prior investigation

clutch_data2 |> 
  group_by(REGION) |> 
  summarise(mean(na.omit(HATCHING_SUCCESS)), 
            sd(na.omit(HATCHING_SUCCESS)))

Priors

hatching_success.priors <- prior(normal(0.72, 0.5), class="Intercept")

Random effect modelling

null model

null.model.formula <- bf(HATCHING_SUCCESS ~ 1, 
                         family = Beta()) 

null.model <- brm(null.model.formula, 
                  data=clutch_data2, 
                  prior=prior(normal(0,1),class="Intercept"), 
                  warmup=500, 
                  iter=5000, 
                  seed=123, 
                  cores=2, 
                  save_pars = save_pars(all=TRUE), 
                  sample_prior = "yes", 
                  chains=2, 
                  thin=5, 
                  control = list(adapt_delta=0.95))

priors

clutch_data2 |> 
  group_by(REGION) |> 
  summarise(mean(na.omit(HATCHING_SUCCESS)), 
            sd(na.omit(HATCHING_SUCCESS))) 
#get_prior(model1.1.formula, data=clutch_data2)
hatching_success.priors <- prior(normal(0.72, 0.5), class="Intercept") + 
  prior(normal(0,1), class = "b")

Fixed effect modelling

Basic model

model1.1.formula <- bf(HATCHING_SUCCESS ~ 1 + REGION + scale(FEMALE_MASS) + (1| FEMALE), 
                         family = Beta())

model1.1 <- brm(model1.1.formula, 
                  data=clutch_data2, 
                  prior=hatching_success.priors, 
                  warmup=500, 
                  iter=5000, 
                  seed=123, 
                  cores=2, 
                  save_pars = save_pars(all=TRUE), 
                  sample_prior = "yes", 
                  chains=2, 
                  thin=5, 
                  control = list(adapt_delta=0.95))
## Compiling Stan program...
## Start sampling

Temporal model

model1.2.formula <- bf(HATCHING_SUCCESS ~ 1 + REGION + scale(FEMALE_MASS) + scale(DAYS_IN_TREATMENT) + (1| FEMALE),

model1.2 <- brm(model1.2.formula,

Model diagnositics

#--- distribution check ---#
pp_check(model1.1, type = 'dens_overlay_grouped', ndraws=150, group="REGION")

clutch_data2.naomit <- drop_na(clutch_data2, FEMALE_MASS)
preds <- posterior_predict(model1.1, ndraws=250, summary=FALSE)
model1.1_resids <- createDHARMa(simulatedResponse = t(preds), 
                              observedResponse = clutch_data2.naomit$HATCHING_SUCCESS, 
                              fittedPredictedResponse = apply(preds, 2, mean), 
                              integerResponse = 'student')
plot(model1.1_resids) ; testDispersion(model1.1_resids)

## 
##  DHARMa nonparametric dispersion test via sd of residuals fitted vs.
##  simulated
## 
## data:  simulationOutput
## dispersion = 0.15629, p-value = 0.016
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
